  "prompt": "How does magnesium react with HCl?",
  "response": "When magnesium (Mg) reacts with hydrochloric acid (HCl), a single displacement reaction occurs, producing magnesium chloride (MgCl\u2082) and hydrogen gas (H\u2082). The balanced chemical equation for this reaction is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Mg (s)} + 2\\text{HCl (aq)} \\rightarrow \\text{MgCl}_2 (\\text{aq}) + \\text{H}_2 (\\text{g})\n\\]\n\n### Explanation of the Reaction:\n1. **Magnesium (Mg)**: A reactive metal that readily loses electrons to form a +2 ion (Mg\u00b2\u207a).\n2. **Hydrochloric acid (HCl)**: A strong acid that dissociates in water to produce H\u207a and Cl\u207b ions.\n3. **Reaction Mechanism**:\n   - The magnesium atom reacts with the hydrogen ions (H\u207a) from the HCl.\n   - Magnesium donates two electrons to two H\u207a ions, reducing them to hydrogen gas (H\u2082).\n   - The Mg\u00b2\u207a ion combines with two Cl\u207b ions to form magnesium chloride (MgCl\u2082), which remains dissolved in the solution.\n\n### Observations:\n- Bubbles of hydrogen gas are produced.\n- The magnesium metal dissolves as the reaction proceeds.\n- The solution may become warm if the reaction is exothermic.\n\nThis reaction is a classic example of an acid-metal reaction and is often used to demonstrate the reactivity of magnesium.",
